## How sessions are isolated

| Resource | Isolation |
|----------|-----------|
| Baileys socket | One per userId |
| Auth credentials | `auth_info_baileys_<userId>/` |
| Message history / settings | `pro_data_<userId>.json` |
| QR code / connection state | In-memory per session |
| WebSocket events | Only sent to clients that IDENTIFY'd with the same userId |

---

## Backwards compatibility

- The old `/api/*` endpoints still work and use the **global** `sock`/`proData` from the original code.
- The new `/api/u/:userId/*` endpoints use isolated sessions.
- You can gradually migrate frontend calls from `/api/...` to `/api/u/${userId}/...` without a big-bang rewrite.

---

## Scaling notes

- All sessions are in-memory (Map). A server restart requires users to re-scan QR.
- For production with many users, consider persisting session tokens to Redis so sessions survive restarts.
- Each Baileys socket maintains a persistent WhatsApp connection; monitor RAM for large deployments (~30–50MB per session).
